          "body": "The narrator inserts a retrospective flashback (the events of 2:6-9 precede those of 2:1-5 chronologically) that resets to Joshua's dismissal of the tribes to their inheritances — the moment the conquest generation dispersed into the land. Verse 7 states plainly what made that generation faithful: they 'served the LORD all the days of Joshua' and through the extended leadership of elders 'who had seen all the great work of the LORD.' The mechanism of their faithfulness was visible memory — they had been present for the Exodus events, the Jordan crossing, the conquest miracles. Their knowing was experiential, not inherited. When Joshua died at 110 (2:8 — the same age as Joseph, Genesis 50:26, a detail not lost on the Hebrew audience) and was buried in his inheritance at Timnath-heres (2:9), the generation of eyewitnesses passed from the scene. Verse 10 delivers the chapter's most ominous sentence: 'there arose another generation after them who did not know the LORD, nor yet the work which He had done for Israel.' The Hebrew word for 'know' (yada) is relational and covenantal — this is not intellectual ignorance but the absence of experiential, tradition-transmitted, living knowledge. The generation gap is not geographic or political but theological: the transmission of knowing broke. Howard Hendricks observed that Christianity is always one generation from extinction — Judges 2:10 is the biblical proof text for that warning."
